{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"377f42dc-ca99-4e84-9936-7075de073d45","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2 / .NET 9** — great, that supports all modern patterns.\n\n**Recommended approach:**\n\n- **`TestContext`**: Inject via a public property (classic) or via constructor (MSTest v3+).\n- **Sync init**: Constructor or `[TestInitialize]`.\n- **Async init**: `[TestInitialize]` returning `async Task`.\n\nYou can only have **one** `[TestInitialize]`, but it can be `async Task` and contain both sync and async work:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; set; } = null!;\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task Setup()\n    {\n        // Synchronous setup\n        var name = TestContext.TestName;\n\n        // Asynchronous setup\n        await SomeAsyncService.InitializeAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void Test1() { /* ... */ }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `[TestInitialize]` can return `void` (sync) or `Task` (async) — use `Task` if you need `await`.\n- `TestContext` is set by the framework *before* `[TestInitialize]` runs, so it's safe to use there.\n- For **class-level** one-time setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (also supports `async Task`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"37686e46-e730-4eeb-9b9d-af84a397a0f9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or the `[TestContext]` property. In MSTest v3, you can inject `TestContext` via constructor.\n\n2. **Sync initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method or constructor.\n\n3. **Async initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with `async Task` return type (supported in MSTest v2+).\n\nLet me give a concise, accurate answer.\n\nIn MSTest 3.x:\n\n\n- `TestContext` can be injected via constructor parameter\n- `[TestInitialize]` supports `async Task`\n- `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` are also available\n\nThe key constraint is that you can only have one `[TestInitialize]` method, so if you need async setup, make that single method async rather than trying to mix sync and async initialization.","outputTokens":781},"id":"7584d3e0-74b9-4a5b-aba7-6ef4126679f3","timestamp":"2026-04-05T02:00:38.000Z","parentId":"2305e36e-bd07-4259-8591-ae8f435a76da"}
